<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-weight=
: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;=
 letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">Distressed meme st=
ocks</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhl=
LXBvcGNvcm4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5046b1a0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote last month</a> that =E2=80=9C=E2=
=80=98if you buy AMC stock it comes with popcorn=E2=80=99=C2=A0is the great=
est capital-markets innovation of the century so far,=E2=80=9D and I meant =
it. AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. needed money, to deal with debt maturit=
ies and to expand its business. It has not had a particularly great few yea=
rs due to, you know, pandemic etc. Traditionally if you are a company that =
needs money to deal with debt maturities, and you have not had a great few =
years, you will have a hard time raising that money. Your cost of capital w=
ill be high. The investors who are willing to finance you will be tough, me=
an investors who ask for a lot in exchange for the money you desperately ne=
ed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then along came the meme-stock phen=
omenon, in which enthusiastic retail investors steer billions of dollars to=
 more or less troubled companies because it is fun. And AMC gleefully=C2=A0=
embraced its band of meme-stock investors, going so far as to offer them a =
free popcorn for owning the stock. And the investors responded. Last month =
AMC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24460016.25995=
3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQvY=
mlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhyZWUtc3BhY3M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B466dca32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> raised $587 million=C2=A0</a><em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhyZWUtc=
3BhY3M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC466dca32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">in one day</a>=C2=A0</em>by selling stock =
to enthusiastic investors at about $50.85 per share. The stock had never cl=
osed above $35.68 in AMC=E2=80=99s history until that week; it closed yeste=
rday at $33.43. You just can=E2=80=99t get much cheaper capital than that.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can, of course, get=C2=A0<em>more expen=
sive=C2=A0</em>capital than that. And the people who offer that more expens=
ive capital are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24=
460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtM=
DctMTUvcmVkZGl0LXRyYWRlcnMtYXJlLXVwZW5kaW5nLXRoZS13b3JsZC1vZi1jcmVkaXQtaW52=
ZXN0aW5nLXRvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBabdc1a8a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pretty sad about the meme-stock ph=
enomenon right now</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Clothin=
g chain Express Inc., prison operator Geo Group Inc., coal miner Peabody En=
ergy Corp. and others have, like AMC, seized on their popularity among day =
traders to seek equity financing -- an option historically out of reach for=
 firms with their debt loads.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99=
s a problem for distressed-credit funds, where corporate failure is a key p=
art of the investment thesis.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Their strateg=
ies often center on identifying companies that are out of options, providin=
g last-resort financing and calling the shots throughout the workout proces=
s. Their controversial tactics -- in which workers are often left bearing t=
he brunt of the pain -- can lead to huge payoffs, including outright owners=
hip of the cleaned-up corporations.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yet opp=
ortunities are dwindling.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s eerily quiet out there,=E2=80=9D said Colin Adams, a senior managing d=
irector at corporate advisory firm M3 Partners, where he focuses on debt re=
structuring. =E2=80=9CYou have the twin monsters of fiscal stimulus and low=
 interest rates, and this phenomenon with meme stocks adds a whole new dyna=
mic.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One problem is t=
hat if your strategy depends on failing companies looking for expensive fun=
ding, the fact that failing companies are sometimes magically rescued by ch=
eap capital from meme-stock investors can just seem unfair. You are in the=
=C2=A0<em>business=C2=A0</em>of charging companies large amounts of money f=
or risky financing. To see a bunch of retail investors do it cheaply, as a =
<em>hobby</em>, is very frustrating.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anothe=
r problem is that distressed investors often do capital-structure arbitrage=
 trades, buying debt that they think will do well in a restructuring and he=
dging it by shorting stock that they think will get wiped out. The problem =
with this trade is that if a company gets memed, its stock (which you are s=
hort) can shoot up thousands of percentage points, but the bonds (which you=
 are long)=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t going to trade to 200 cents on the dollar, m=
ostly because nobody trades bonds on Robinhood. And so distressed funds =E2=
=80=9Ccan no longer count on a predictable stock market to hedge massive, m=
ultipronged bets=E2=80=9D: Normal relationships between stocks and bonds ha=
ve broken down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also stocks go up in bankru=
ptcy?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors confronted this=
 reality with a trio of mall owners that filed for bankruptcy over the past=
 year -- CBL &amp; Associates, Pennsylvania Real Estate Investment Trust an=
d Washington Prime Group Inc.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All three saw=
 their stock prices fluctuate -- often surging on little underlying news --=
 as they approached and then entered Chapter 11, where shareholder value ge=
ts wiped out almost as a rule.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brian Sheehy=
, the founder of IsZo Capital Management, which takes long and short positi=
ons across firms=E2=80=99 capital structures, started shorting the mall own=
ers as they began to buckle under the weight of unpaid rent and monthslong =
store closures.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI predicted they w=
ould go bankrupt, and I was right -- but I still lost money,=E2=80=9D Sheeh=
y said. =E2=80=9CThis stuff now will go straight up into your face until th=
e day they file,=E2=80=9D he said, adding that =E2=80=9Cthe incentives are =
all thrown off.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is=
 an article of faith among many investors in meme stocks=C2=A0that, by push=
ing up the price of their stocks, they are sticking it to hedge funds. The =
theory seems to be roughly that lots of big hedge funds are mainly in the b=
usiness of betting against AMC, and that by pushing up the price the meme-s=
tock investors will destroy those hedge funds. This is clearly sometimes tr=
ue:=C2=A0Melvin Capital did get <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9tZWx2a=
W4tY2FwaXRhbC1sb3N0LTUzLWluLWphbnVhcnktaHVydC1ieS1nYW1lc3RvcC1hbmQtb3RoZXIt=
YmV0cy0xMTYxMjEwMzExNw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBda517c09" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">notably blown up</a> by Gam=
eStop Corp. investors in January, and some of the distressed-debt anecdotes=
 here are about funds getting hurt on short bets.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">But the bigger, stranger picture here is that the meme-stock investo=
rs are messing with the=C2=A0<em>business model=C2=A0</em>of a lot of distr=
essed-focused hedge funds. You=E2=80=99re supposed to be able to find compa=
nies that are failing and then make money either by betting against them or=
 by giving them expensive financing. Now sometimes you will correctly ident=
ify a company that is failing, and it will be struck by lightning and shoot=
 up instead. Your credit analysis and capacity to finance hairy companies a=
nd sharp-elbowed negotiating skills won=E2=80=99t matter because sometimes =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24460016.259953/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDkvbW9uZ=
Xktc3R1ZmYtdGhlLW1lbWUtc3RvY2tzLWtlZXAtY29taW5n/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB69=
10f633" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">be=
ing bad is good</a> for a company=E2=80=99s stock price. It makes the whole=
 notion of fundamental analysis riskier and more suspect.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Undermining the whole notion of fundamental analysis might b=
e =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bad for the world? =E2=80=A6 but it is interesting.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere: =E2=80=9CAMC share price gets <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMS8wNy8xNC9hbWMtc2hhcmUtcHJpY2UtY3V0LWluLWhhbGYtYXMt=
cmVhbGl0eS1zZXRzLWluLWZvci1tZW1lLXN0b2NrLWludmVzdG9ycy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB7f18c9cd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">cut in half</a> as reality sets in for meme stock investors.=
=E2=80=9D</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black=
&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; paddi=
ng: 16px 0px 5px;">SPAC SPAC SPAC</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Man, I d=
on=E2=80=99t know what is going on here, but it=E2=80=99s too weird not to =
tell you about it. On Monday, a special purpose acquisition company called =
Lionheart Acquisition Corp. II <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci=
9kYXRhLzE4MDI0NTAvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDkwOTY4L3RtMjEyMTk2N2QxX2V4OTktMS5odG0/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBac293226" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">announced a merger</a> with a company called MSP Re=
covery LLC, a company =E2=80=9Cspecializing in Medicare Secondary Payer rec=
overy rights and the recovery of improperly paid Medicaid.=E2=80=9D Basical=
ly someone=C2=A0gets in a car accident, they go to the hospital, Medicare p=
ays their hospital bills, MSP hunts down the auto insurer of the person who=
 hit them, it sues the auto insurer, the auto insurer settles, and MSP pays=
 part of the settlement to its lawyers, gives part to the Medicare provider=
, and keeps part for itself. That sort of thing. This is more fully explain=
ed in the MSP/Lionheart <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhL=
zE4MDI0NTAvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDkwOTY4L3RtMjEyMTk2N2QxX2V4OTktMi5odG0/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBdb021605" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">investor presentation</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24460016.=
259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMTQv=
ZmxvcmlkYS1sYXd5ZXItZXgtcGFyYXRyb29wZXItZm9yZ2UtYS0zMy1iaWxsaW9uLXNwYWMtZGV=
hbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8ffa212b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: sol=
id; background-color: #ccc;"> a Bloomberg News article</a> that captures mu=
ch of the flavor of the deal. Let me select a few numbers from the article =
to give you a sense:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the dea=
l is completed, it will go down as =C2=A0one of the most unusual SPAC trans=
actions yet. Aside from the disparate backgrounds of its principals, the co=
mpany forecasts zero revenue this year, there are none of the traditional c=
o-investors participating and three of Lionheart=E2=80=99s directors have r=
esigned in recent months. And at a $32.6 billion valuation, it=E2=80=99s th=
e second-biggest proposed SPAC transaction after Grab Holdings=E2=80=99 $40=
 billion merger scheduled for later this year.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Okay so the key numbers there are =E2=80=9Czero revenue=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cat a $32.6 billion valuation, it=E2=80=99s the second-b=
iggest proposed SPAC transaction.=E2=80=9D You don=E2=80=99t see a lot of c=
ompanies with zero revenue and a $32.6 billion valuation. But, you know, fi=
ne, some companies have zero revenue and enormous opportunities; maybe it i=
s not<em> that</em> strange for a company with no revenue to raise billions=
 of dollars at an enormous valuation. How much is MSP raising from its deal=
 with Lionheart? Here is the table of sources and uses from the <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MDI0NTAvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDkwOTY4=
L3RtMjEyMTk2N2QxX2V4OTktMi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCdb021605" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">investor presentat=
ion</a>:</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/i8CrLRiPR9tA/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/i8CrLRiPR9tA/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MSP is raising $230 million at a $=
32.6 billion valuation, and spending $70 million of it on fees. The SPAC=E2=
=80=99s shareholders are getting 0.7% of the company. Its existing private =
shareholders are keeping 99%.[1] It gets a $32.6 billion headline valuation=
 by selling $230 million of stock. This is nowhere close to =E2=80=9Cthe se=
cond-biggest proposed SPAC transaction,=E2=80=9D measured by=C2=A0<em>trans=
action size</em>. It=E2=80=99s just big measured by=C2=A0<em>headline valua=
tion</em>. MSP is not raising an especially large amount of=C2=A0money, but=
 it=E2=80=99s raising that money by selling a tiny slice of its stock.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually even that overstates it, because it as=
sumes that Lionheart=E2=80=99s shareholders will all want stock. After a de=
al like this is announced, the SPAC=E2=80=99s shareholders <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24460016.259953/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDgvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtc3BhY=
y1tYWdpYy1pc24tdC1mcmVl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbafe0bd8" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">get to decide</a> whether =
to roll their SPAC shares into the new company or just get back the $10 in =
cash that they paid for their shares. Lionheart=E2=80=99s shares closed yes=
terday at $10.00. That suggests they want their money back.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">As that Bloomberg article notes, SPAC deals=C2=A0usually c=
ome with =E2=80=9Ctraditional co-investors,=E2=80=9D institutional investor=
s who buy stock in the company in a PIPE (private investment in public equi=
ty). This gives the company more money and greater certainty (because PIPE =
investors, unlike SPAC investors, do not normally have withdrawal rights), =
and it helps to validate the SPAC=E2=80=99s valuation: If big institutional=
 investors invest alongside the SPAC on the same terms, SPAC shareholders c=
an have some confidence they=E2=80=99re getting a good deal. This is so tra=
ditional that=C2=A0<em>there=E2=80=99s a line for =E2=80=9CPIPE Capital=E2=
=80=9D in Lionheart=E2=80=99s sources and uses</em>, even though there isn=
=E2=80=99t any PIPE capital. I don=E2=80=99t know why that line is there, o=
ther than because it was in the bankers=E2=80=99 template and they forgot t=
o take it out.=C2=A0It kind of draws attention to the absence of a PIPE?</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also the lack of a PIPE =E2=80=9Cmay be partl=
y due to questions over valuation=E2=80=9D[2]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Hedge fund Marshall Wace, an existing Lionheart investor, d=
iscussed participating in a PIPE at a valuation closer to $10 billion, acco=
rding to a person with knowledge of the matter, who asked not to be identif=
ied discussing confidential information.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
=E2=80=9CA wide range of valuations, which didn=E2=80=99t include the entir=
e scope of what=E2=80=99s included in the company now, were discussed at a =
very preliminary stage nearly six months ago,=E2=80=9D Ruiz said.</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is going on here? I have truly no =
idea, and I recommend that you read the Bloomberg article, which touches on=
 many weird things I haven=E2=80=99t even mentioned. (=E2=80=9CA law firm o=
wned by [MSP Chief Executive Officer John] Ruiz and MSP=E2=80=99s chief leg=
al officer will the exclusive lead counsel for MSP, meaning it stands to re=
ceive 20% of all recovered payments, according to a filing.=E2=80=9D MSP pl=
ans to pay more of its =E2=80=9Cgross revenue=E2=80=9D to its CEO=E2=80=99s=
 law firm than it keeps for itself. That=E2=80=99s weird!)</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">But here=E2=80=99s one way to think of it. If a company can=
 go public at a $32.6 billion valuation, that is helpful for the company an=
d its existing investors. If you go public at a $32.6 billion valuation by =
selling 10% of your stock for $3.26 billion, that=E2=80=99s great: You have=
 a high valuation and also $3.26 billion. But if you=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0</em>do that, you still get some benefit by going public at a $32.6 b=
illion valuation, even without bringing in any money. If you sell 0.1% of y=
our stock for $32.6 million, then you have a $32.6 billion valuation and es=
sentially no new money. (After paying bankers etc. you are at best breaking=
 even.) But then the=C2=A0<em>next=C2=A0</em>time you try to sell stock, yo=
u can say =E2=80=9Clook, we have a public-market valuation of $32.6 billion=
.=E2=80=9D And then if you sell 1% more of your stock for $326 million, tha=
t=E2=80=99s real money. Or if you sell it for $250 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re giving you a huge discount to our public-market valu=
ation=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s real money too.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">In general you=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>go public=
 at a $32.6 billion valuation by selling 0.1% of your stock for $32.6 milli=
on. Even if you could find someone to buy that little stock for that much m=
oney, it=E2=80=99s just too weird a deal and your bankers won=E2=80=99t let=
 you. But there are a lot of SPACs out there chasing deals, and if you want=
 to do a weird deal you can probably find a SPAC that will let you.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This doesn=E2=80=99t make any real sense as a fina=
ncial matter, but as a matter of psychological anchoring it does seem helpf=
ul=C2=A0for a company with no revenue to be able to say =E2=80=9Cwe went pu=
blic at a $32.6 billion valuation.=E2=80=9D And if that valuation came from=
 selling 0.7% of its shares, and wasn=E2=80=99t validated by any institutio=
nal investors in a PIPE, it=E2=80=99s still something. Even if it=E2=80=99s=
 not validated by most of the <em>regular=C2=A0</em>investors in the SPAC, =
and a lot of them ask for their money back. The Bloomberg article notes:</p=
><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of all the players, Ruiz stands t=
o gain the most. His 70% stake in the firm is worth close to $23 billion at=
 the combination price. MSP and Lionheart executives will be allowed to sel=
l 10% of their shares as soon as the transaction is completed, with the rem=
ainder subject to a six-month lock up.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Is he going to be able to sell that 10% for $3.26 billion? I have =
no idea. But having headlines saying the company went public for $32.6 bill=
ion won=E2=80=99t hurt.</p>
